## Java Field-Only Data Access Rule

In this repository, generating or using getters/setters for DTOs and simple data models is prohibited. Use direct public-field access only.

- MUST:
  - Declare DTO fields as public (`public`).
  - Access data via fields: `request.name`, `response.status`, etc.
  - Prefer Lombok annotations that do NOT generate getters/setters: `@Builder`, `@NoArgsConstructor`, `@AllArgsConstructor`, `@EqualsAndHashCode`, `@ToString`.
- MUST NOT:
  - Add getters/setters (including Lombok `@Getter`, `@Setter`, `@Data`) to DTOs.
  - Call `getX()/setX()` or `isX()` in controllers, services, or tests.
- SCOPE:
  - Applies to classes in `com.example.dto` and to all new request/response/value types in the project.
  - If future entities require a different approach (e.g., JPA), create a dedicated rule that explicitly exempts them.
- MIGRATION:
  - Replace `getX()/setX()` with direct field access `.x`.
  - For booleans, use `.available` instead of `isAvailable()`.
  - Jackson serializes/deserializes public fields out of the box; getters/setters are not required.
- REVIEW GATE:
  - Reject changes that add getters/setters or Lombok annotations that generate them.
  - Propose converting to public fields and updating call sites.

Examples

Bad:
```java
@Data
public class UserRequest {
    private String name;
}
// ...
if (req.getName() == null) { /* ... */ }
```

Good:
```java
@Builder
@NoArgsConstructor
@AllArgsConstructor
public class UserRequest {
    public String name;
}
// ...
if (req.name == null) { /* ... */ }
```
